rics, and to reinterpret these works as meditations on the ethics of compiling and using data. In this way, Notework recasts information collection as a personal and expressive activity that comes into focus against large-scale systems of knowledge organization. Finding resonance between today's digital culture and its nineteenth-century precursors, Reader honors our most disposable, improvised, and fleeting textual gestures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAuthors, Englishy19th centuryxNotebooks, sketchbooks, etc. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLiterary formxHistoryy19th century. 70(DE-588)4014777-00(DE-627)1063387490(DE-576)208909400aEnglisch2gnd 70(DE-588)4035964-50(DE-627)1062450150(DE-576)209015608aLiteratur2gnd 70(DE-588)4074285-40(DE-627)10464950X0(DE-576)209193182aLiteraturgattung2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aVictorian literature.  abook history.  aformalism.  agenre.  aliterary fragments.  anotebooks.  anotes.  astyle.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362797040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627970423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627970/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles